Daily menu of an obese child: do not eat breakfast and dinner sausages
More than one third of children aged 9-13 have overweight problems, where overweight affects 9 per cent of the school population and obesity 5 per cent.
Obese children mostly come from families with a lifestyle that is not healthy, according to current research.
The importance of the environment where it is grown for the healthy development of the person, as well as the models that serve as a reference, is again demonstrated.
At the table, obsessive children, for example, feed on sausages at least twice as often as children in families with normal weight.
For dinner, more than 19% of the obese had had French fries the day before the analysis, which is linked to the prevention program "Obesity is not a coincidence."
In overweight children & apos; s families, there is no practice of sports, which is applicable to most current families, where only 15 per cent of children responded that their parents, at least once a week, find time for physical exercise.
Survey of 900 children
The survey was conducted at the end of last school year and nearly 900 children from basic education from all over the Czech Republic participated in the survey.
It was already the second edition of the program "Obesity of is not a coincidence," supported by the General Health Insurance Company and Unilever.
So far, more than 12,000 children have participated in the project from the 4th to the 8th grade.
An adequate diet and a lot of exercise in the family are determining factors, which significantly reduce the number of children with overweight and even obesity.
"Only half of the children surveyed have responded that they have five meals per day according to the scheme: breakfast, lunch, food, snack and dinner, which is one of the basic conditions for a healthy diet," one of the results of the survey.
No breakfast but with a meatball for dinner
The specialists warn that, in a healthy development, the details, which also count, such as having a fixed hour for family breakfast, are important.
In Czech, however, only 23 per cent of school families have breakfast at the same time.
In most families, each one has breakfast alone.
But the worst thing was to find out that in 10% of households nothing is breakfast.
Breakfast is, however, the basis for a correct daily diet.
The study shows that in families of obese children, unhealthy fries are used much more often.
Almost all - regardless of weight - drink sweet drinks daily (70%).
As a rule, more than 40 per cent of the children surveyed do sport, however, their parents enter this result to less than half, only 15 per cent.
Make your diet
The next phase of the study allowed the chosen children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to create their own diets from all possible offers according to their tastes and opinions.
"The food preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15, from the point of view of a healthy diet, are far from ideal."
Among your favorite foods are pasta, meat and sweets
"The popularity of sweet drinks is above all alarming," is noted in the final report of the study.
As a main food, the palm is taken away and followed closely by the meat of birds.
Practically, children always reject the leaven and taste for fish and vegetables is very low.
Change to healthy habits
At the same time, the study shows that children are willing to change their eating habits if they receive fair information.
"In the control group of the study participants, who completed the questionnaire after the end of the prevention program" Obesity is not a coincidence, "there was in many cases a major change in favour of the principles of healthy feeding," it is noted in the results of the study.
It draws attention, for example, to the sweet drinks, where many children would start to prefer normal and running water.
Children would also more often choose poultry and fish for main food in the questionnaire and would restrict the consumption of fresh food and flour derivatives.
