IBM history: from the cheese cutter to space flights
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, its original name being Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted in 1924 - originally a brand used in the branches of Canada and South America.
The base that led to the birth of IBM comes from the merger of four companies that go back to the 1880s.
He had inventions like the famous "registration watch," which allows to control the entry and exit of the employees.
The architect of the new company was the businessman Charles Rankett Flint, who until 1930 also presided over his supervisory board.
Flint signed the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the management of the company.
The new leader eclipsed the founder of IBM (Watson's ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name indicates, began with the production and sale of all types of business equipment, from meat and cheese cutters to register boxes.
During the first four years Watson led the company, the billing doubled by $9 million and the large expansion of the company began on the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, almost forty years later, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA to guide space flights (to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System / 360 series.
The classic "pecés," which established the standard of computers of that time, arrived on the market under the name IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer full advice and services of high value added.
The strategy IBM has paid for these last three years is the concept of "Smarter Planet," that is, "a smarter planet."
Its objective is to make more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned and circumstances improved, for example, in the transport and management of cities.
For the trade sector, IBM recently presented the "Smart Commerce" platform that allows retailers to manage the full business cycle.
