How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies at that time sold in most cases only trips to the socialist bloc, as the travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime leaned west and the trips of Czech tourists were then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (that is, also the Czech Republic) were not allowed to travel freely and individually even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation, if not, the individual travel was not possible.
The travel agencies offered in those days also trips to the West, but one had to line up with a sleeping bag and spend like this all night, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to "politically unreliable people," who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without a guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of the Czechs spent their holidays in their own country, so there were a large number of cabins and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way of travel of the Czechs has been a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was the no longer going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million holiday trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, that the current favorite destination, Croatia, could not travel freely until 1989, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, visa exemption was imposed for travel to neighbouring Western European States, leading to a huge wave of short-term visits, particularly to Vienna or Germany.
The Czech Slovaks, for a long time, did not see themselves fed up with the West excursions, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, the Czech groups were sleeping in the parks in tents, as our then income did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to take with them food (conserved, sausages, etc.) to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was increasing and with it also the average wages, which around 1997 led to an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in the demand for travel, the agencies began to prepare the travel regularly from 1997 using the charter flight connections, which led to an incredibly low travel prices compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for the volume of passengers.
By the end of the 90's last century, the Czechs were already travelling without a visa to almost all developed countries, except the US, which further simplified our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened in 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from Czech to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists have taken place every year, making countries far away and warm. This winter will already be flown directly from Czech to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries are currently visiting about 100,000 Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this time, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, more than 15 thousand Czech kroner per head have been spent on foreign travel, including expenses at the stay site.
