Before becoming the new face of the extreme right in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another guy who aired his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted having carried out a massacre in Norway in July, which left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from being alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time preceding his attack on his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social networks.
After this summer's tragedy, the researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do you find them?
Easy - just get on Facebook.
"We realized that it was not so difficult to reach them," says Jamie Bartlett, the main author of a recent report on European digital populism by the British study centre DEMOS.
Facebook's personal information cache is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographic characteristics with scientific accuracy - the way sellers have been using for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million fans of right-wing groups all over Europe and then directed them ads, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey that asked about their educational level, attitudes towards violence and optimism about their own future.
On arriving through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries - all without leaving the office.
"It's a whole new way of doing an investigation," Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, male and angry by immigration.
However, in a kind of turn, "those who combine their online activism with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen."
DEMOS's work is just an example of how Facebook is becoming a new and important tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything, from health problems to social trends as expressed in "Like," messages on walls and state updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook's "data supernova" is generating an increase in research, boosting the number of academic works with the name of the site in the title up to almost 800% in the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you could not approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to find people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You would have to go through the party, and they would never allow you access," Bartlett says.
"Facebook removes all that - you go to them directly."
Others say that the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno, from the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues, found that university students who spoke about their drunkard feats on Facebook had a significantly greater risk of having drinking problems than students who remained silent on the subject.
Moreno suggests that students' colleagues, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student publish too many state updates with their drunkards.
