7 Lessons from Steve Jobs's lost interview, shown in a theater this week
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the genius from technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find more revealing, in an interview with Jobs recently rediscovered to which it has been dusted as a advance of a series of special projections in the larger markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about the commercial processes and workflows of the products.
He was certainly a self-recognized designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a yonki of the flow diagrams - a man who believed that many executives suffered "a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds (The Triumph of the Nerds) on the opening of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working hard on his new NeXT computer company, waiting for popular Internet adoption.
While a small part of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during his transport.
It was only after Jobs died that a full copy of VHS was discovered in the director's garage.
This file material, slightly reedited, is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute lost interview that reaches the Landmark cinemas on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and commercial strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers - from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also moments when the perfectionism of Jobs comes to the surface, where it seems impatient because of Cringely's questions, pushing it to go faster to the most important issues or arguments.
Filmed before the Pixar era, iPod or iPhone, there is something strangely prophetic about the lost interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies do right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computer.
One thing is to read posthumous assessments of Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the edge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, it went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences of The Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"Over the years in the business, I always asked," Why do you do things? "and the answers they give you invariably are," Oh, that's just the way it's done. "
No one knows why he does what he does, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs takes his efforts to simplify Apple's accounting into detail.
Disconcerted by the way the costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was made to the eye of a good cuber, and then adjusted with a "variable" - developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine the commercial costs in detail.
On the Pope's joke:
Jobs tells the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
It has been written widely about the device, but the euphoria of Jobs here by describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a public phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT & T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
"We were wrapping things around the world a half a dozen times and yelled through the public phone and went back a minute later to the public phone next door," says Jobs with a little laugh.
"We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world."
The two of us, we didn't know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing - it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and asking to speak to the Pope, while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the American diplomat, the two of them broke out in the face just before the Pope himself was awakened to go and answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and the phone sale with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call.
Shortly after his 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and formed my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees."
Jobs later became one of HP's employees who visited the company's research laboratories in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first table computer ever made."
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a little cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I'd get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste my time with that machine and write programs for her.
On improvising innovation:
At several points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Soon in his career, as he dedicated himself to selling a handful of base plates, a client asked him if he could set up the whole team.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to find out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while in Apple, remember the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember having dramatic arguments... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got tired and left and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
On large companies losing strength:
Long before he led the Apple Renaissance, Jobs prophetically anticipated how many industry leaders would stumble into their vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better photocopiers and printers, so what?"
You have a monopoly of market share, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is this kind of people who end up running the companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the decision-making forum.
The genius of the products that led to this monopoly position will rot because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened in Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the '90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
On innovation as an artistic expression:
"There is a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows."
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make - some things you can't make electrons, glass makes them, robots make them, factories make them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end everything is reduced to taste - it is reduced to trying to expose you to the best that a team of humans has done, and then try to adapt those things to what you are doing.
Picasso said good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've never been ashamed about stealing great ideas.
What in part made Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who were casually the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for computer, I could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
