How to detect a lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and omnipresent are deception and lie in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging charges of sexual harassment with several women; each side is accused of lying to the other.
The administrators of Pennsylvania State University have been charged with perjury for allegedly hiding reports that a retired football coach was sexually attacking children.
Last week, French President Nicolás Sarkozy was "caught" with an open microphone claiming to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed races and convulsed countries.
The New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist, Anthony Weiner, made a fool of himself with his fast-to-rebuttal dissidents for the irrefutable test.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramatrimonial relationship.
And again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
The legends about the traps in the school and university exams are very widespread.
There have been cases in which teachers have given the test responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that the unknown were lying three times in the first 10 minutes of getting to know each other.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies," is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a table game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have You," the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the last six decades at prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that old myths about lie have been rebutted.
Liars do look into the eyes.
They don't always stutter, chew, blush or worry.
It cannot be concluded either that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can reach the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation and times.
I spent several years looking at scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that the detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world - especially if its professional responsibilities include recruitment, interviews, or the management of negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, making them feel at ease, handling their own emotions and feeling intuitively how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more "self-oriented lies," while women say more "self-oriented" lies -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie less often to their partners than non-married people (but the lies they often say tend to be "huge").
We also know that if you are perceived as an evil, the others will feel less guilty in lying to you.
How do you know if someone's lying?
First, observe the usual conduct of the subject.
This is called "creating a baseline."
It helps provide benchmarks to measure changes later.
Observe the subject's position, laughter and vocal feature.
You better know if someone usually hits with their feet all the time to not make unfair accusations when I see their feet hitting in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceptive, verbal and non-verbal behavioral groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as alarm signals, not as evidence of deception.
People who cheat can freeze the top of the body by trying to remember their history, they can point their feet towards the door, lean towards an exit, change their position significantly, or exhibit a "post-interview exhale" -- that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of position once all difficult questions are over.
The interrogators often falsely see that the interview is over only to seek that post-interview relief.
It also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up to the bottom and used the time past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a search for her nationally.
People who cheat can also use a distancing language: "I didn't have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when he answers a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... until I... understand."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning signal.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
