Climate Adversity Stopped the Economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez's management, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality have increased, foreign investment has dropped and the economy has contracted
The 2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of government of Mario López Valdez, self-called of change, which generated high expectations regarding the progress in the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, there is no growth, but there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, in addition to causing millions of losses for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of economic activity in general of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the report of frost effects issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582 thousand 835 hectares were damaged, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main sinister crops were vegetables, corn and garbanzo.
The fall in economic activity has led, until November, to a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of state unemployment during the first three quarters of the year has been accelerated, as while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the economically active population, for the second quarter the rate has increased to 5.28 per cent, and between July and September the average has continued to increase to 6.19 per cent, a rate that in the number of people has dropped to more than 74 thousand Sino69, compared to the first half of the 969.
Reduced liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been carried out since public policy.
"What is being seen is a growth in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market for the purposes of a resource restriction by the legislation that was passed in Congress to combat money laundering, as for people who illegally grab dollars it is not easy for them to work, invest them and use them in something," he said.
Detained migration
López Cervantes noted that in the increase in unemployment there is also a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the state in search of work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, first because of the difficulties in entering, and second because they are already having a lot of difficulty in finding work, these people are staying and demanding sources of work here in the state, which causes unemployment to rise," he said.
Informality
The analysis of the Sinaloese labour market is aggravated by the high level of informality that predominates between working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in the state work without being listed as a worker before any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another of the state's labour delays are low wages, the entity has the lowest remuneration in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Social Security Institute and the Ministry of Labour and Social Security.
The average monthly income of the Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7 thousand 375 pesos.
FDI contract
In addition to the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 there was the largest decline in foreign direct investment over the last 10 years, according to the Ministry of Economy from January to June of State FDI amounted to $630 thousand 697, a fall of 87.74 percent from the $5 million 143 thousand 312 recorded during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the State Government's Secretariat for Economic Development accounts for a total investment of 17 billion pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
In the context of economic contraction, the state government applied in July to the State Congress for the approval of a credit of 3 billion pesos, which would be intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of 2 600 million pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of indebtedness in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government of Mario López Valdés shows a lack of management capacity of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 he lacked the harmonization of the will of the different sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa this year has really been very poor, we have to work hard to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we have to redouble efforts, we have to align the effort of all and especially the already synchronized good march of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic clarity
Loredo López stated that events like the early year's frost stopped the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including the frost, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows for an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing well below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefining vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the National Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said that it is necessary to prosecute the state towards more dynamic productive activities.
"In general terms we have observed that work has been done, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that the full potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated," he said.
Work to be done
The President of the Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better links the Government's efforts.
"In general terms I would say that the Government has been working to achieve good results in different areas, there are some progress in economic development, but it is important that a long-term programme be developed," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its conduct of public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is being more inclusive, I can say that there is work done and I believe that the Government is aware that there is work to be done," he said.
