Valid cut "analog blackout" in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analogue signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) rejected the constitutional disputes brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree that advance the so-called "analog blackout" from 2021 to 2015, by not meeting the eight votes necessary to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to make the transition to digital terrestrial television more concrete.
With this result, the constitutional dispute promoted by the Senate of the Republic was rejected because it did not reach a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and this is in force.
The draft judgment, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed to declare the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a power reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the reservation of law.
In favour of the project only Zaldivar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero themselves voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional disputes to challenge the decree, and by admitting the demands, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions in it arranged for the digital transition.
The plenary of ministers also decided to dismiss the application brought by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also by Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Minister-President said that he did not agree with the project's arguments that the federal executive could not structure the measures for the preparation of the public administration through general rules.
"I also do not consider that if it did, the autonomy of the regulatory body would be affected," and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the federal executive, who has a constitutional mandate, the State's leadership.
The replacement of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes that the world has experienced in recent years, and results in better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone change, he said, would be to postpone the benefits of digitization, which involves a decision of public interest, which does not have only a technical dimension, "since it covers economic, social, political and national security issues."
These issues, he said, "require the operation of the entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic rectification of the State, includes a group of powers which the Constitution leads to the power of the State Executive."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and has done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the contested decree, which in some way invades the sphere of competence of the Congress, is providing in the administrative sphere for the observance of the laws issued by the Legislative, he said.
They analyze the possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data released by the PRP the difference between the first and second place of the election of governor is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total records.
The possibility of "vote by vote" is a reality in terms of this year's electoral process in Michoacán, where according to the data released by the Pre-Trial Electoral Results Program (PRP) the difference between the first and second place of the governor's election is just 27 percent, even without the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this regard, the President of the General Council of the Michoacán Electoral Institute (ICES), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just on 9 November, the electoral body adopted a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with federal electoral reform.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not approve its Political Constitution or the State Electoral Code or the Electoral Justice Act, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal deadline to enable them to enter into force in the present electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the time limits provided for in the State Official Newspaper Act, on the grounds that he had some objections.
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional dispute promoted by the local legislature and called the state president's vote "invalid and illegal" to constitutional reforms, since he has no right to "punish or veto them."
Interviewed about the possibility of "vote by vote," María de los Ángeles Llanderal stated that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the ICES it will be possible to make partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may be given in cases where: the results of the minutes do not match; there is no record of scrutiny and computation in the file of the box or does not hold the office of the president; or, where there are obvious errors or changes of the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the vote received in all polling stations may be made where there is an indication that the difference between the alleged candidate who won the election in question and the candidate who obtained the second place in the vote is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is the express request of the party representative and / or coalition who nominated the second of the candidates.
The total count of the vote may also be made if, at the end of the ordinary ballot, it is established that the difference between the candidate alleged to be the winner and the candidate in the second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express request from the representative of the political party whose candidate was the second, in which case the electoral packages that have been partially counted will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that in this situation there is the choice of Morelia, where according to the PRP the difference between the first and the second place is only 0.16%, but without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total records.
