The designated Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet on Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has placed Italy on the brink of the economic disaster and put the entire eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said that he will present the President with the outcome of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "frame is now well delineated," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has driven its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a hard austerity package required by European leaders to regain the beaten confidence in Italy.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability put the performance of the Italian BTP bonds to 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would be very supportive of this government."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were considerably driven by the support of the PDL party of Silvio Berlusconi, whom the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that the efforts of Professor Monti are intended to have a good result," said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the central right-wing party, to the press.
The support of the PDL, the largest party in Italy, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti Government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what will probably be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in their efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks joined the pressure to warn that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations.
It will end your round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was named on Sunday by Napolitano, which has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief break at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between the uncertainty as to whether the new Prime Minister will succeed.
To save Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 billion euros, would be too much for the current financial defenses of the eurozone.
Monti has said that his government should last until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before they advance the elections.
Monti has said that he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that it should be made up only of technicians, an indication of their reluctance to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources noted that mutual distrust and disagreements between parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
