Secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome gives details of the air accident where Governor Francisco Blake lost his life and seven more people
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident in which Governor Francisco Blake Mora lost his life, and seven other people, indicate that the helicopter was directly hit on the ground in full structural integrity, without the pilot trying to make a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate for flying.
"The elements that appear to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the land, the masks had contact with trees 25 meters away where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so he had the necessary requirements to transport the staff.
In addition, he said that research in the impact area does not report the appearance of parts on the ground.
"In one search it is reported that there are no parts or components of the ship elsewhere, the impact was presented in a structural way.
"The helicopter design was for 19 passengers, with adequate requirements to transport the passengers.
The terrain has a slope of seven degrees at 30 degrees of inclination.
For the time being, the secretary said that it is a priority to have the results before possible; however, the investigation can last several months, it could even reach one year.
For its part, Gilberto López Meyer, general director of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the helicopter of the Presidential General Staff operated at cruise speed and that this happened on an ascending soft ground.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact," he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the research:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical normativity the flight was carried out under the rules of visual flight, this means that the crew must have visibility during the flight and the terrain.
Weather conditions:
The reports at the SAICM placed conditions for take-off, as the aircraft moved towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico, there were low-height nubosity layers.
Selected routes:
It is likely that by the conditions of nubosity the crew will have sought an area of less elevation and greater visibility towards the valley of Cuernavaca.
Impact location.
The impact coordinates and the last record of the radar aircraft match, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft remains in a reduced area:
The information available so far makes it possible to assume that the impact occurred on a straight and side path.
The pattern of dispersion of the aircraft & apos; s remains makes it possible to assume that the helicopter was hit on the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the site of the accident, there is still no evidence in the remains of the ship of any kind of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9 thousand 200 feet over the average sea level, the ground has a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it was expected to disarticulate along the course.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After the thorough search in a wider area than the agreed site, around the accident, no dispersed parts of the aircraft have been found, which strengthens the presumption that the impact was presented under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find obesity gene
Social Security leads research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Social Security Institute (IMSS) announced that it is conducting a research to discover the gene of obesity in children and young people, called the 'Genetic protocol of obesity of childhood and adolescence', which will allow for markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Speciality Hospital of the National Medical Center Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutriologists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the research, the population is invited to participate whether or not it is right, to go to the sports units participating in the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests are carried out to the minors, every Saturday from 8: 00.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Mexico Poniente) and that since October 8, the activity has been carried out in the Nezahualcoyolt Sports Unit (State of Mexico East).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (southern Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify in Mexican children and young people risk factors to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On November 14, he said that the goal was to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about the physical activity and heredophamiliary history of diseases, with the aim of avoiding risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or renal failure.
He noted that the Saturdays are applied to all participants anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure taking, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (it is intended to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López noted that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight increase in children.
'Health surveys in 1999 and 2006 noted that in just six years there was an increase, for boys, of 77 per cent in obesity, and for girls of 47 per cent; in terms of overweight, a dramatic rise was also observed, 'said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for the markers is based on the fact that the country's population differs from others because of its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent of Indian American heritage, 30 percent European and 5 percent African and this condition is reflected in the genes that are associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the comprehensive evaluation of children, which allows to detect if they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acanthosis) in the neck and forearm, which indicate the likelihood of metabolic and even prediabetes alterations.
The information is handled confidentially, the doctors deliver it in writing to the parents, who are explained to each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarianism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, to remain most of the day sitting in front of the TV and to use means of transport rather than walking short distances.
It is also due to the high caloric intake, that is, the increased consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates (tamals, bread, pizza, burger, etc.) with high fat and protein content and the genetics discussed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid potholes
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops polymer-modified asphalt to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of the environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs sent by the pavement were to be met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200 thousand pods each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of the Valley of Mexico, said Rafael Herrera Nájera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who said that if the process of building and maintaining an asphaltic pavement is the right one, the pods could be reduced in quantity or even completely eliminated.
In its conference A technological opinion of the potholes, given in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory in charge of it develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to the asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and therefore the formation of potholes.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of which are high molecular weight, called asphalnos, and others of low molecular weight, called malnos, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt is that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees Celsius its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees Celsius it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the asphalt resistance is not uniform, but is being modified during the day according to the environmental and temperature conditions, the specialist in chemical engineering warned.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphaltic folder, made up of small stones bathed in asphalt and then compact.
Each of the little stones that constitute the folder, he pointed out, is bathed with asphalt.
By passing the vehicles and generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, they would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
On the asphaltic folder, it abounded, is placed a last layer called a rolling folder, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As it is the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphaltic folder and provide friction on the way.
As the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling folder also requires the appropriate thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care of.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphaltic folder.
When the ground is wet, the water is spread inside the folder and it is difficult to get out, this causes a smoothing of all the layers of the pavement and, therefore, the formation of potholes.
In the process of forming a pothole, he said, the first to wear out is the bearing film and only then the asphaltic folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but it is a process that should be followed to the first signs with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of potholes and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always go in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is fulfilled, in order to avoid the formation of potholes frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already in the market and allow to repair potholes easily and without the need to use high temperatures.
