So was the work of the Chaleño who identified Alfonso Cano's body.
A Cali lofoscopist passed to history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano."
The work of these staff members is key.
On November 4, a lofoscopist of the Cali STI went into history as the man who confirmed the identity of the chief of the Farc: "Alfonso Cano," through the collation of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lophosphopists working in the STI section, that week was the "availability" shift for Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the area of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where he often had to stay in the jungle for more than five days to reach the site where the bodies were to be identified.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after the corresponding courses, he specialized in lofoscopy, which is the study of the skin of friction, that is, the palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano to Eliazar was warned to wear minimum clothes for three days.
Something big was waiting for you.
On Friday night he left for the Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that one of them was suspected to be the man who directed the world's oldest guerrilla, so they asked him to carry Guillermo León Sáenz's decadacular card (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the investigation team at the site where the body was located, he did not recognize it because of its physical appearance, as it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He was without a beard, dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the body to those of the card.
His eye did not fail him: it was "Alfonso Cano."
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the chief of the Farc.
In search of the print
For a dactiloscopista of the Sijín de Cali the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González, at the press conference for the operative against "Cano," is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, with no margin of error, which can become key in the resolution of crimes.
Apart from the identification of bodies, the lofoscopists support investigations into crimes such as theft and murder and confirm the identity of the captured persons.
When captured, many criminals present false ballots or have no papers.
We take the fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The investigator said that, in a case of theft, he had to remove a piece of wall from a house, for in that place the thief had supported his hand to take out a safe full of jewels and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not appropriate surfaces to make a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the fingerprint from the whole hand and identify the offender, who had participated in different burglary," he recalled.
The prints can also rule out or reaffirm suspects in cases of murder.
They recently found a dead man, with bottles of liquor around him.
The investigation found that a family member could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a print on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the killer, he does place him at the crime scene.
A STI dactyloscopist explained that in the objects "the prints are removed with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a transplaner or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said the STI expert.
He clarified that not everything is as shown in the CSI TV show.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that is touched becomes a print.
However, if it can be used, if the respective check is done.
The "outraged" challenge authorities in New York City
Hundreds of protesters were clinging to Zuccotti Square to camp.
A large part attended the eviction order and moved to a nearby paruqe.
The members of the Occupa Wall Street movement challenged the New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to enter again, under a court order, into Manhattan Square from where they were evicted early in the morning and by trying to occupy another park in the Great Apple.
Hundreds of protesters were clinging to Zuccotti Square, where they wanted to access thanks to a court order that allows the "outraged" to camp again in the place, while another part of the movement responded to the eviction by occupying a park further north of the city, where there have been new arrests.
"Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp again in the square, we are going to set up somewhere else and continue the legal battle to return to Zuccotti, as well as through peaceful sit-ups and demonstrations," said one of the spokespersons of the "Occupa Wall Street" movement, Mark Bray.
Bray detailed that the "indignant" response to the eviction from his camp personally dictated by the mayor of New York, Michael Bloomberg, came to the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forced evacuation of the site and allowing the protesters to stay in camp.
In addition, the "outraged" proceeded to the occupation of a new park located at the confluence of the central Canal Street and the Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to the Holland tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, and property of the Trinity Church parish.
At least for an hour they managed to take the place, but then the police came and proceeded to arrest some of the protesters, although Bray was unable to confirm the specific figure, while he assured Efe that he saw several journalists who were also handcuffed.
The organization claims that several hundred people had settled at that point, where a delegation of religious leaders had already moved to show support for the members of the movement and had tried to mediate with the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square - which is a privately owned compound - is still closed pending the holding of a judicial hearing scheduled for this very Tuesday in which the legality of the evacuation of this early morning should be analysed.
Some of the protesters displaced there carried and distributed copies of this court order at this time and even handed them over to the officers who were guarding the square, which led to "some small clashes," Bray said, who reported that some officers beat the demonstrators.
The court order prohibits the authorities from evicting members of Occupa Wall Street or from applying "laws that were published after the occupation began or from allowing protesters to access the park again with shops or other properties they used previously."
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that, due to this court order, the city had suspended the reopening of space to the public and to the protesters, which he warned, however, that local laws do not allow them to reinstall with tents and sleeping bags.
The regator personally defended the early eviction of Zuccotti Square, an operation in which about 200 arrests were carried out and which was decided because the protesters were "violating the law."
Bloomberg explained that he gave the order to evacuate the square because it was becoming "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and, in some cases, to hurt other people," as "some businesses had received threats" and neighbors feared "for their quality of life."
"This morning's eviction was gross and shows that Bloomberg is more interested in preserving the financial interests than those of the American workers," said the spokesman for the movement, who accused the mayor of "disrespecting freedom of expression."
The leaders of "Occupa Wall Street" also indicated that they plan to organize "great actions" by Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and trade unions, to commemorate the two months that the protests last, which began on September 17.
