Japan reborn after the earthquake
GDP grows by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the fall spiral that started in March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still convalescent of the devastating earthquake that became a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster that the country has suffered since World War II.
The first estimates by the Government of Tokyo amounted to $300 billion in material losses, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have been reduced.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the data of the Gross Domestic Product between July and September served to move on, definitely: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% at the annualized rate.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the highest rate of growth from January to March 2010.
The recovery is explained, in part, by the rebound of the purchase of machinery to restore the areas ravaged by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1 per cent, compared with a 0.9 per cent decrease in capital expenditure from January to March, the first fall after six months of continuous increases.
However, the true repulsive of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites the use of crises to strengthen - or rebuild - the infrastructure, to use the gaps to grow from scratch.
Japan has, above all, been awakened by the development of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60 per cent of Japanese GDP.
This variable climbed by 1%, driven by increased expenditure on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo has been entrusted to the internal market, when the yen - the Nippo currency - has become one of the "shelter values" chosen by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the euro area and the shady forecasts of the US, a privilege that weighs as a slab in the accounts of the exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, the products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of large technological groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, blamed their weak results between July and September on the yen's contribution.
While markets continue to be besieged by the EU's peripheral countries, the Yoshihiko Noda government does not lower its guard.
"We must be attentive to the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said State Secretary for Economic Policy Motohisa Furukawa yesterday.
And, indeed, the prospects are not encouraging.
The Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) stated that most member countries presented more clear signs of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the turning points in the world economy highlighted that the main powers are slowing down.
As it went down four tenths to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 August.
The euro area, even, was below the average, which is at level 100, when it was precipitated eight tenths to 99.13 points.
Athens refuel the doubts
Papadimos says the adjustments will be approved, but the conservatives will not sign any written commitments
With the outlying risk premiums fired and the uncertainty reinstalled in the parquis, Greece continues to entangle the maze leading to the emergence of the major European debt crisis.
The feeling that the "consensus" of the new Greek Transitional Government is more imposed by the demands of Brussels than by a genuine conviction of the political forces is beginning to be confirmed by facts.
While the new Prime Minister, Lukas Papadimos, warned yesterday that there is no alternative to structural reforms and that the one-hundred-day period agreed upon in his appointment may be short to implement them, the leader of the conservative party New Democracy, Antonis Samaras, assured that he will not support new austerity measures in any case and reiterated his demand for new elections by the scheduled date of February 19.
"The main task of this Government is to implement the decisions of the 26 October summit," Papadimos said, opening yesterday a parliamentary debate that will culminate tomorrow with a vote of confidence to the new Executive.
A package with 24 programmes to boost employment, the reform of the staff disciplinary code and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras' message does not clear doubts about his position: "We have committed ourselves to helping the transitional government, but we have not committed ourselves to anything else."
The conservative leader was a step further in his pulse to the EU and the IMF, the bodies that must unlock the 8 billion that Athens urgently needs, and he made it clear that he will not give his approval to any commitment letter of compliance with the adjustments.
But the European Commission, even though it had the impact of the order of the Papandreu referendum, had reiterated yesterday that its demand was firm: it would not unblock aid if the new Government and the leaders of the main Hellenic parties did not sign "a written compromise without ambiguity and as soon as possible."
Economic Affairs spokesman Amadeu Altafaj explained that the troika inspectors will return "very soon" to Athens to discuss with the new government "what is needed to pay for the sixth tranche" of 8 billion, although there is no final date.
The Greek wood still has a long thread.
Mrs. Sofia: "They are instruments for progress and hope"
The Queen highlights the "preponderant" place of Spain in relation to this type of finance
Spain "has reached a world-wide top in the role of microfinance."
Queen Doña Sofía recalled yesterday that the country has become the second donor in the past two decades to this interchange of cooperation, whose "essence" stated that it lies in being a "tool for social progress, justice and the hope for a better future for all humanity, based on trust in the human being."
Yesterday the Queen opened the Fifth World Microcredit Summit in Valladolid with the conviction that "there is no doubt" that this type of operation is "absolutely indispensable" to the achievement of the Millennium Goals set by the United Nations on a horizon 2015, and "especially in the one that aims to halve the volume of people living on income below a daily dollar, setting the" poverty line. "
Spain "continues to work" to extend the network of beneficiaries "to all corners of the planet, and takes on this task with" responsibility, "said Doña Sofía, who hoped that the initiatives and contributions that come from the Summit, which will continue until Thursday," will ensure the creation of new capacities and better opportunities for the poorest, and especially for women, "which are the main beneficiaries of these loans.
There are "many achievements" and "many challenges we face."
The Microcredit Summit is not only a forum for discussion, but also a platform for "two basic goals."
His Majesty explained that by the end of 2015, there are 175 million poor families who have access to these financial services and 100 million of those households are expected to leave the poverty line they are in.
The momentum in the conception of micro-credits in Spain and the rest of the world "has followed the path begun years ago in a pioneering way" by Muhammad Yunus, emphasized Dona Sofia as an "act of justice and due recognition."
He described the father of this tool as an "admirable idealist in the universal cause of the fight against poverty," whose work he has known for 15 years, when the Queen travelled to Bangladesh to learn about her lending policy on the ground.
