Finally, Queen Doña Sofía concluded her intervention by encouraging those present to participate in the debate and in the search for solutions to make progress in the fight against poverty.
"Ethical Imperative"
Foreign Minister Trinidad Jiménez warned that solidarity "is an ethical imperative" for every democratic state.
In this regard, he stated that it would be a mistake to link cooperation with developing countries to times of economic gain, as it is a "permanent obligation."
Jiménez considered that micro-credits are "a serious and rigorous policy dedicated to the eradication of poverty," and now "more than ever" the governments of developed countries must work on criteria of solidarity and not let it be the victim of the cuts.
For Spain, microcredit is "one of the main lines of development cooperation."
For her part, the Secretary of State for International Cooperation, Soraya Rodríguez, applauded "the success" of giving "confidence" to the people "excluded from those who all close the doors"; and the mayor of Valladolid, Francisco Javier León de la Riva, welcomed those present to a city that "opens its doors infected by the spirit of solidarity."
