Papademos: Greece to implement a new adjustment plan
Greece is going to need a new adjustment plan to straighten its economy.
This is what Prime Minister Lucas Papadémos stated on Monday, 14 November, before Parliament; he also added that the 100 days that have been given to his union government would not be sufficient to achieve that objective.
"To make efforts leading to the recovery of the economy, we need the support of our European partners and a new budget adjustment programme," said the Head of Government, who delivered his first public speech during the opening of the debate on the vote of confidence in Parliament on Wednesday.
The implementation of the decisions taken at the euro area summit on 27 October will be the "main task" of the new government, as the country's stay in the euro area "is at stake," he added.
As a result, Papadémos has expected that the country's government deficit will be reduced "to about 9%" of GDP by the end of the year, after reaching 10.6% in 2010 and 15.7% in 2009.
The right rejects new austerity measures
Antonis Samaras, the head of the right-wing group, on Monday showed his support for the measures already adopted to try to get out of the debt crisis, but has warned that his party will not commit itself to additional austerity measures.
"We will not vote for new measures," he said during a meeting with the members of his "New Democracy" party.
He agreed with the objectives of deficit and debt reduction, as well as the fight against waste, but against any policy that would prevent economic recovery.
To Olli Rehn, European Commissioner for Economic and Monetary Affairs, who warned that the IMF and the EU would not unblock the necessary EUR 8 billion loan without a written guarantee of all parties' support for the planned measures, Antonio Samaras replied that his word would be enough and that he would not sign anything because of external pressure.
An expert committee states that euthanasia and assisted suicide should be legalized
Canadians live by denying death, according to the report of the Royal Society of Canada
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls for Governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not only in cases of cancer.
Canadian society lives by denying death.
In fact, only 9 per cent of Canadians are willing to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they wish to die and make provisions to that effect.
This is one of the conclusions of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, with the participation of six experts from various fields, including ethics, legal and medical.
This committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code so that assisted suicide and euthanasia are allowed, when the patient considers that option and has been judged competent to make the decision.
To begin with, experts cite a recent survey of the Economist Intelligence Unit that compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
Although Canada is in tenth place, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has generated a culture in which people are afraid to deal with the issue of death."
With or without medication, 77 per cent of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, according to experts selected by the Royal Society of Canada.
And, even though most Canadians want to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in the hospital.
Overall, the highest rate in this regard is recorded by Québec, where 86% of deaths occur in the hospital.
With regard to the delicate issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report reached conclusions that do not coincide with the position of the federal Government, which has already stated that it does not wish to amend the Criminal Code in relation to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who have also studied the situation in all countries where such practices have been legalized or do not constitute a criminal offence, there is no evidence that the fact that they are not considered a criminal offence has not caused an abuse of their application, i.e. the use of euthanasia or of assisted suicide with non-competent persons or who have not given their consent.
Jocelyn Downie, co-author of the report, said yesterday for teleconference that, on the contrary, there were more excesses in those countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide have not been legalized.
"In Canada euthanasia is practised, although it is clearly illegal."
"In Canada, assisted suicide is practised, although it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians, favourable to euthanasia
Let us remember that 85% of Canadians have already spoken out in favour of euthanasia, as they believe that it would allow people whose death is near to alleviate their suffering, according to a 2010 Angus Reid survey.
In addition, 66 per cent believe that legalizing euthanasia will not imply that the lives of elderly or disabled people have less value.
With regard to persons who have experienced assisted suicide, 41 per cent of respondents believe that a trial should not be initiated against them.
In relation to the maintenance or interruption of health care to a patient, the situation is not so clear, as the authors of the report indicate.
Furthermore, among its recommendations, it is suggested in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of health care, if legally rejected, does not constitute a criminal offence.
The expert committee also calls for the training of health professionals in the duty to respect the fact that a patient rejects end-of-life care without fear of facing a complaint.
In the area of palliative care, the committee calls for Governments, health care institutions and doctors to work together to ensure the best palliative care, and not only in cases of cancer.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in health institutions in Canada, the committee requests that, unless it serves to reduce physical pain, it be considered euthanasia and subject to the same procedures.
Other experts express reservations
Other experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the findings of the report of the experts of the Royal Society of Canada.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, has described the position of the experts who sign the report as "extreme," inter alia, because euthanasia is not limited to the end-stage patients.
"This leaves the door open to a situation where someone who is tired of living and is over 18 years old can ask for help to commit suicide," Deschamps said, who yesterday consulted a summary of the report.
Mr Deschamps also stressed that the authors of the report seemed to give priority to personal autonomy over any other value of society.
He added, however, that "in society, there are labels and limitations."
Health law specialist Margaret Somerville also expressed her "strong opposition" to the report's conclusions, which she described as "a manifest in favour of euthanasia."
Margaret Somerville, who also belongs to the Royal Society of Canada, particularly questions the lack of abuse in certain countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legal, as in the Netherlands and Oregon.
