A Russian scientist has collaborated with the Iranian nuclear program
A Russian scientist, Vycheslav Danilenko, has collaborated with Iran in the development of a detonator that can be used with a nuclear weapon, an American NGO specializing in atomic risk said on Monday.
For the identification of the researcher, the Institute for International Science and Security (ISIS) is based on a recent report from the International Atomic Energy Agency (AIAA) and other documents issued by that UN agency.
The AIAA expressed last week its "serious concern" about a "possible military dimension" of the Iranian nuclear programme.
According to ISIS, based extensively on AIAA documents, Danilenko, born in 1934, had worked for three decades, since the 1960s, in a Soviet military nuclear centre in Tcheliabinsk (Oural) and had participated in the manufacture of synthetic diamonds by explosion.
In 1989 or 1991, he would have left the centre to form a company focused on the production of "nanodiamateurs" in Kiev.
The economic problems of his company led him to contact, in 1995, the Embassy of Iran in Ukraine.
It is then believed that it cooperated with the Iranian programme between 1996 and 2002, before returning to Russia.
In its last report, AIAA mentions that there are "clear indications that Iran is developing" a nuclear detonation system "with the help of a foreign expert, who not only knew the technique well, but also, as one Member State has informed the Agency, worked for most of its career in this technology in the military nuclear programme of its country of origin."
Crimes and crimes against Muslims have increased by 50 per cent
Crimes and crimes against Muslims have increased by about 50 per cent between 2009 and 2010, while, during the same period, the remaining types of racial and religious violence have decreased or increased only slightly, according to statistics published by the FBI on Monday.
According to these figures, the total number of acts of violence committed against Muslims has increased from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, or 49 per cent, compared with a 13 per cent increase in the case of violence against Catholics, a 4 per cent reduction in crimes against Jews and an overall 14 per cent increase in the number of anti-religious crimes and crimes.
The total number of "hate crimes" has grown slightly to 6,628 cases, of which 47.3 per cent are due to racial differences and 20 per cent to religious differences, according to the FBI.
"After a decline in 2009, it is a matter of concern that these types of crimes and crimes have again increased," said the human rights organization Human Rights First, "the increase in acts of violence against Muslims is particularly significant," the organization added in a statement.
"Human Rights First has long noted that violence against Muslims, as well as all types of hate crimes, should be considered a serious violation of human rights," adds a head of the organization, Paul Legendre.
"The US government can and must strive to put an end to such abuses," he added, considering that such efforts could include an improvement of police reports on "hate crimes."
The "hate crime" in U.S. federal law was inherited from the time of the struggle for civil rights.
This legislation was adopted after the death of Martin Luther King to punish acts of violence linked to race, skin colour, religion, origin and, now, sexual inclination.
