Austria
Introduction of a budgetary "gold rule" in the Constitution
The Government of a large social-democratic / democratic coalition in power in Austria has decided on Tuesday to include in the Constitution a budgetary "gold rule" to reduce the public deficit and thus to avoid possible degradation of Austria's sovereign note by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor himself, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when the Austrian public debt reached 74.6%, a figure well above the 60% ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency was reduced at a single level, from AAA to AA +, we would have to pay 3 billion more in interest each year," said Democratic Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger.
Austria is thus responding to a request from the Brussels Summit to the euro area member countries on 26 October: the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, by the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or in an Act with equivalent value.
The scheme adopted by the Austrian Government is close to the "German model," as Germany was the first European country to adopt this type of "rule."
By 2017, the structural government deficit should be reduced by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year and, from 2017, the structural government deficit of the federal State should not exceed 0.35% of GDP every year, while regional states, as well as communes, should present balanced budgets.
The objective is to reduce public debt by 2020 / 2021 on the basis of the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
