Energy policy:
facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be addressed taking into account short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an electoral meeting be the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if you look at the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that there are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic developments will mean the doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing shortage of fossil resources will have to be addressed in order to continue to produce electricity continuously, including the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
That is not the case with Belgium, which has to do with the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor with Switzerland, which is only intended to build state-of-the-art plants.
On the other hand, the Czech Republic, Finland, Poland, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to cite some examples, are moving forward with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, reconstructing a plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality goes against such a discourse.
The Berlin election will lead to an increase in the price of electricity, greater energy dependence due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noted.
The case of Denmark should be considered.
The European champion in the wind sector, of which he gets 30% of his electricity, is also one of the major users of coal and gas due to the intermittent of the wind; for this reason, his CO2 emissions and the price of his electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to our energy policy, our neighbours pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would result in a strong rise in the price of electricity, which would undermine realism to the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not in principle express opposition to this type of energy, as the surveys show.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has lost to building an industrial sector with 125,000 leading jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
It is widely export-oriented and covers a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets that can create non-offshoring jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would be the sacrifice of a large part of these SMEs and the loss of the EUR 6 billion per year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would charge an EPR designed to run for 60 years when the manufacturer's collapse is planned?
To solve the equation of nuclear energy, we must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, as there is no diabolical source.
Areva's development of low-CO2, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with security.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it did not cause consequences either for people or for the environment.
In Chernobil, the accident was due to the reactor design and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of an unprecedented range, which resulted in the death of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
As a result of this progress and cooperation between the security authorities, and the French and German operators and builders, the RPA presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is studied by all the electrical actors who want to build a plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, as it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy applied by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized on the basis of various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the figures policy, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of France's "country of human rights."
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped the headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the Libération newspaper of 23 May) proclaiming in the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters."
However, it is rarely economically analysed.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac set the orientation by stating in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country with about two million immigrant workers," while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take over all the world's misery" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden on French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In its programme, François Hollande merely includes banalities, indicating that co-development will help to solve the "migration problem."
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be cost-effective in the electorate, but it is very expensive economically.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work that summarizes the most recent knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
The limitation of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
The fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, particularly the low-skilled, by pressing for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are rather complementary than substitutes for national workers and are mainly engaged in professions in sectors with a lack of employment.
Unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country with a lack of anesthesiologists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to have a positive impact on the wages and employment of the nationals.
In view of the above, Giovanni Peri estimated that a 1 per cent increase in migration flows represents an increase in real long-term wages of between 0.6 and 0.9 per cent.
And without taking into account the fact that the diversity of immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized US Nobel awards and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, with an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that a 30-year-old immigrant in Germany will make a net contribution (income less expenditure) of EUR 150,000 to the average public budgets throughout his / her life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go and look for the missing growth points "with his teeth."
These teeth, which deterred immigrants, had exactly the reverse effect.
Europe invented democracy, it only needs to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious good, but also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember that, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the twentieth century it has suffered the tragedies of the World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, to Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that, for democracy to triumph over its enemies, it would be sufficient to exercise the vote and in the most direct way possible.
We know from Napoleon the "Little One," that it was a thought.
Universal suffrage, although a necessary condition for democracy, is not sufficient in itself and can even become a "tool of oppression," as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
