Cards with "no contact" chip are widespread
The world's chip card lounge starts on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an optimistic atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in world sales of microprocessor cards (bank cards, SIM-card phones, etc.), with a total of 6 billion units, according to the Eurosmart cabinet calculations.
The most powerful segment is that of non-contact technology, which allows to pay for common transport or purchases by simply bringing the card closer to a reader.
This year, 460 million cards with no contact chip will be sold worldwide, 320 million more than the previous year!
Their share should continue to increase in 2012 (580 million units are expected) and represent about 10% of the world's chip card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe, which has long been lagging behind the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the non-contact payment sector.
About 26 million Visa bank cards already have this function, which is accepted at 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 Visa cards are being used without contact.
But the large surfaces work for four.
Carrefour issued 2.5 million free-of-contact Pass MasterCard cards this year.
In order to make the top run, however, banks need to make them available to their customers.
"There are two large French establishments that have committed themselves to systematically disseminating to their customers, bank cards equipped with the system without contact," says Gérard Nébouy, general director of Visa Europe France.
Banks test payment by mobile phone
But it is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
At present, there are few devices equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, which is essential for carrying out transactions.
"They're lagging behind."
"But I should finally experience a real boom next year."
"We anticipate that 80 to 120 million units will be sold in 2012 around the world," explains Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and next June in Caen.
The iPhone will be equipped with about 200 customers and collaborators with a case that allows for no contact payment.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société générale has also stated yesterday that it is preparing the marketing of an offer that allows its customers to pay without contact through their mobile.
From Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about the links between Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the terrorist group Al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram, which has long been suspected, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, the Algerian Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs, Abdelkader Messahel, even stated that Algiers already "has certainty."
"The way both organizations operate and intelligence reports show that they are cooperating," he explained, without providing any further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the abduction of two French in Niger last January would have resumed the walkways.
Raped in a Niamey restaurant by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the following day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, the French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips that belonged to the terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The survey of the calls made indicates to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers especially captured the interest of the researchers: one leads to a Nigerian who long remained in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is allegedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but we must certainly wait for more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"We have known for years that the sect has enjoyed external financial and intellectual support and is increasingly active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, such "support" had become increasingly evident in the evolution and discourses of Boko Haram or in its operational modes, which now involve the use of Kamikazes or increasingly complex explosive devices and in the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has since been pushing Abuya to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have, in fact, long seen the group as a community of unworthy enlightened people.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and fundamentalist magnet Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (meaning, in hausa, "Western education is a sin"), it incites the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Muslim Nigeria.
In this poor region, the partnership is living a rapid success.
It politicizes and demands strict respect for the sharia, while its militants are in the fight against the wicked central government.
The latter focus first on churches, bars and administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active and attacks on police stations increased.
Abuya's reaction was, as usual, widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 were recorded dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested in life, is killed in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and left its northern feudos.
The past Christmas, he claims an attack that causes 80 deaths in Jos and then another in Abuya.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuya, in particular the protected police headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of this kind.
In August, the United Nations headquarters became its first international goal.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which would range from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, is a matter of concern to all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and the Somalis of Al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram appears as a new threat in the centre of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to "share all the information."
