The Nord Stream, the new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly communicates Western Europe with Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must provide gas to meet the needs of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, has wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the opening of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that directly communicates, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Similarly, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have together turned the steering wheel of the valve that controls the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic metres of Russian gas will reach Western Europe each year through a first had 1,224 km that communicate the region of St. Petersburg with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed by the end of 2012, which will provide a total of 5 billion cubic metres of gas, that is, sufficient to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work presents the atmosphere of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow to supply gas directly to Germany, avoiding the land course by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
At once, these two countries lose something of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact," referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But price is a weakening of the energy Europe, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has been able, in just five years, to succeed in its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," said François Fillon at the opening of the gas pipeline, demonstrating to what extent the large contracts in the gas sector are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom's managers, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect it against the anchors of the ships.
It is based at the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, out of caution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for the Nord Stream society.
It was also necessary to strengthen measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in all its length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in the waters of Sweden, but the project leaders gave up on the view that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to establish itself permanently at sea off the coast.
"In case of a failure, we will interrupt the passage of the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, gas from the pipeline shall therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that there will be a leak, as they have planned reunions that are expected to have a leak every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline is ensured by means of a submarine robot, carried over by a ship, which carries out external inspections, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced into the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one metre, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without any repair.
The flow of the gas is simply guaranteed by pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
The German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (9% each), joined it.
These five companies have set up a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and exploit the pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented to the company, for a period of 25 years renewable, all the gas transport capabilities.
"Gazprom will be paid for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported," says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been carried out by 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be EUR 7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure they will not exceed their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of expenditure.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas output door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has received a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people the taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its white broken leaves, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Mode Mode, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch a book of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant to the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the banquettes.
This type of notebook was highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the present taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who since then became responsible for the brand in Mode.
And he made it.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first few years has remained far away, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, as the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and educated.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers in its beginning, now has about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the city centre, and has been able to impose its identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists expose their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard tapas on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer covers... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that causes envy: in the fall of 2006, Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19 per cent of disabled people are seeking employment.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a determined public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled doubled the average rate: 19 per cent, compared with 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Disheartening?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, general director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable.
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, much remains to be done."
It should be mentioned that disabled unemployed people continue to face many obstacles to access to employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not completed high school and, out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared with 38 per cent on average.
In other words, there are many issues that are particularly difficult to return to the world of work and that "are the key to the problem," says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; the mentality of people advances, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the Association IMS-Entreprendre for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a level of knowledge about low disabilities," with "excessive representation of wheelchair, physical or intellectual poor."
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the target of hiring 6% of disabled workers, which was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, which date from 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6 per cent.
"We now reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, general director of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution," as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has created great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, particularly among large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59 per cent of companies with between 20 and 49 workers have disabled employees in their staff, compared with 82 per cent of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
